  "summary": "Kumotsumi and Tsubaki discuss the motives behind the killer's theatricality, specifically the decapitations and the creation of locked rooms. Kumotsumi suggests the killer is performing for an audience. Mochizuki directs attention to the deceased Uma, noting that he is holding a luxurious, dull brass key with a complex shape and a carved lily on the handle in his left hand. Mochizuki also points out Kusanagi’s corpse, which is surrounded by shriveled orange or mandarin seeds. While Detective Jinguji suggests the killer might be mentally ill or a fanatical logic enthusiast, Mochizuki posits that the killer is a highly confident narcissist who may be intentionally leaving misleading trails. As the forensic team arrives, the group is instructed to investigate the source of the oranges.\n\nIn a Victorian-style second-floor reception room, the narrator waits with Matsuzaki. Mutsuji teases the narrator, suggesting the case is just beginning and that the killer might reveal themselves if found. Mochizuki asserts that the locked room was likely an inevitable part of the killer's aesthetic design. While the narrator questions the next steps following Ito's death, Mochizuki remains calm, appearing to wait for something specific. The scene concludes when Kanai enters the room; he appears pale, unhealthy, and looks like a weak scholar, gazing at the group with unease.",
